    <title>Combined summary - Proposal: Bundled payments</title>
    <updated>2023-06-29T03:02:13.478309+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/lightning-dev/2023-June/003977.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>Thomas Voegtlin has proposed an extension to BOLT-11, the Lightning Network protocol, that would allow invoices to contain two bundled payments with distinct preimages and amounts. This proposal is aimed at services like Submarine swaps and JIT channels, which require prepayment of mining fees for non-custodian exchanges. By implementing this change in BOLT-11, it would level the competition field between lightning service providers. Currently, using dedicated clients like Loop is necessary for such exchanges, putting competitors without an established user base at risk of mining fee attacks.The proposed change involves including two preimages and two amounts in the BOLT-11 invoice: one for the prepayment and one for the main payment. The receiver would need to wait for both HTLCs to arrive before fulfilling the pre-payment. If the main payment does not arrive, the pre-payment would fail with a MPP timeout. Once both payments have arrived, the receiver fulfills the HTLCs of the pre-payment and broadcasts the on-chain transaction. The decision to make this feature required or optional lies with the service provider.Matt Corallo expresses skepticism about introducing new changes to BOLT-11, stating that getting support from the entire ecosystem may be difficult. He suggests focusing on specifying a standard way of doing swaps and building it on OMs (Onion Messages) for increased privacy.There are differing opinions on whether this extension should be implemented in Bolt 11 or Bolt 12. Thomas believes that including it in Bolt 12 makes more sense due to the active development and implementation of Bolt 12 by all parties involved. However, Matt points out that it will likely take years for Bolt 12 to become the dominant payment method on Lightning.Overall, the proposal aims to improve the competition between lightning service providers by allowing reverse submarine swap payments to come from any wallet. However, the narrow set of requirements for users, such as having an on-chain wallet separate from their lightning wallet, may limit its practicality. It remains to be seen whether this extension will be implemented and how it will impact the Lightning Network ecosystem.</summary>
